value.value: A phenothiazine and traditional antipsychotic agent with anti-emetic activity. Chlorpromazine exerts its antipsychotic effect by blocking postsynaptic dopamine receptors in cortical and limbic areas of the brain, thereby preventing the excess of dopamine in the brain. This leads to a reduction in psychotic symptoms, such as hallucinations and delusions. Chlorpromazine appears to exert its anti-emetic activity by blocking the dopamine receptors in the chemical trigger zone (CTZ) in the brain, thereby relieving nausea and vomiting.
A variant of parapsoriasis in which the plaques are large.
A change in the nucleotide sequence of the MSH6 gene that either inhibits expression or results in the translation of an inactive DNA mismatch repair protein Msh6 protein.
A change in the nucleotide sequence of the PMS2 gene that either inhibits expression or results in the translation of an inactive mismatch repair endonuclease PMS2 protein.
Damage inflicted on the body as the direct or indirect result of an external force, with or without disruption of structural continuity.
Expression of a fusion protein with an apparent molecular weight of 210 kilodaltons that results from a fusion of the human genes BCR and ABL1.
Expression of a fusion protein with an apparent molecular weight of 230 kilodaltons that results from a fusion of the human genes BCR and ABL1.
Expression of a fusion protein with an apparent molecular weight of 190 kilodaltons that results from a fusion of the human genes BCR and ABL1.

Bcr/abl is the gene rearrangement that is associated primarily with the disease chronic myelogenous leukemia and less frequently with acute lymphoblastic leukemia.  This rearrangement results in the formation of the BCR-ABL1 fusion protein.

The lupus erythematosus cell, which is likely a neutrophil with denatured nuclei. It may be found in blood, bone marrow, synovial fluid, cerebrospinal fluid, pericardial and pleural effusions of individuals with lupus erythematosus.
A mature neutrophil with a nucleus having distinct lobes connected by filaments.
Deposition of calcium in the tissues. It may be the result of a metabolic disorder or long-standing infection, or it may be associated with the presence of cancer.
A large, neoplastic T-lymphocyte with an irregularly shaped nuclei and scant cytoplasm that is associated with Sezary Syndrome.
A lymphocyte characterized by a structural or functional abnormality.
An abnormal cell that contains intranuclear and intracytoplasmic cytomegalovirus inclusion bodies.
A benign or malignant, primary or metastatic neoplasm affecting the male and female reproductive system.

A mesenchymal cell showing variable degrees of skeletal muscle differentiation. It is a polygonal, fusiform, round, or bizarre cell with a usually eccentric nucleus and bright eosinophilic cytoplasm sometimes exhibiting cross-striations.
An epithelial cell that occurs in human disease or in models of human disease.
